{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "Dahneke",
        "description": "Dahneke transition-regime correction factor f_D for gas-particle mass transfer. f_D is the ratio J/J_c of the actual particle-surface flux to the continuum-regime flux (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006, Chapter 12, Eq. 12.42): f_D = (1 + Kn) / (1 + 2 Kn(1 + Kn) / α). In the continuum limit (Kn ≪ 1) f_D → 1, recovering J_c with no correction; in the free-molecular limit (Kn ≫ 1) f_D ≈ α / (2 Kn) → 0, reflecting strong reduction in flux for very small particles or very long mean free paths. Migrated from Aerosol.jl src/mass_transfer.jl `Dahneke`.",
        "tags": [
            "aerosol",
            "mass-transfer",
            "transition-regime",
            "knudsen-number",
            "seinfeld-pandis"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-21T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "Aerosol.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-v5x)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H. and Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd Edition. John Wiley & Sons. Chapter 12, Eq. 12.42 (Dahneke transition-regime correction factor for gas-particle mass transfer)."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "Dahneke": {
            "reference": {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H. and Pandis, S. N. (2006) Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics, 2nd Edition, Chapter 12, Eq. 12.42 — Dahneke transition-regime correction for gas-particle flux. Migrated from Aerosol.jl src/mass_transfer.jl `Dahneke` (esm-v5x).",
                "notes": "source_ref: Aerosol.jl@FWrvp:src/mass_transfer.jl:145\n\nUpstream `Dahneke` is an MTK `@component` with 2 parameters (Kn, α) and 1 variable f_D(t) determined by one explicit algebraic equation with no time derivative — purely observed.\n\nEquation (S&P 2006, Eq. 12.42):\n  f_D = (1 + Kn) / (1 + 2 Kn(1 + Kn) / α)   [transition-regime correction, dimensionless]\n\nThe Dahneke formula interpolates between the continuum limit and the free-molecular limit:\n  Kn → 0 (continuum):    f_D → 1                    (no correction; J = J_c)\n  Kn → ∞ (free-molecular): f_D → α / (2 Kn) → 0    (flux strongly reduced)\n\nAt the transition Kn = 1: f_D = 2 / (1 + 4/α); for α = 1 this gives f_D = 2/5 = 0.4 exactly.\n\nThe Dahneke correction is an alternative to the Fuchs-Sutugin factor (fuchs_sutugin.esm). Both reduce the continuum flux J_c toward the free-molecular regime, but use different interpolating polynomials. Dahneke (1973) derived Eq. 12.42 by matching the continuum and free-molecular solutions at Kn = 1; it has no empirical fitting parameters beyond α.\n\nParameter naming: upstream Julia `α` → ESM `α` (Unicode preserved, matching the accommodation-coefficient convention across the aerosol/mass_transfer migration family: uptake_coeff.esm, mass_transfer_coeff.esm).\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-12): purely algebraic expression with a single division of two polynomials in float64; round-off is ~1e-15 relative. rel=1e-12 leaves three orders of headroom — same as maxwellian_flux.esm, which has a similar arithmetic complexity."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-12
            },
            "variables": {
                "Kn": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 1.0,
                    "description": "Knudsen number Kn = λ / R_p, where λ is the gas mean free path and R_p the particle radius. Dimensionless; Kn ≪ 1 = continuum regime, Kn ≫ 1 = free-molecular regime, Kn ≈ 1 = transition regime. Default 1.0 places the system squarely in the transition regime."
                },
                "α": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 1.0,
                    "description": "Mass accommodation coefficient: probability that a gas molecule striking the particle surface is taken up. Dimensionless; range (0, 1]. Default 1.0 (perfect accommodation). Smaller α increases the effective resistance in the free-molecular regime, reducing f_D at a given Kn."
                },
                "f_D": {
                    "type": "observed",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Dahneke transition-regime correction factor (Eq. 12.42): f_D = (1 + Kn) / (1 + 2 Kn(1 + Kn) / α). Dimensionless ratio of the actual flux to the continuum-regime flux J_c: J = f_D × J_c. Approaches 1 for Kn → 0 (continuum) and α / (2 Kn) → 0 for Kn → ∞ (free-molecular).",
                    "expression": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {"op": "+", "args": [1.0, "Kn"]},
                            {
                                "op": "+",
                                "args": [
                                    1.0,
                                    {
                                        "op": "/",
                                        "args": [
                                            {
                                                "op": "*",
                                                "args": [
                                                    2.0,
                                                    "Kn",
                                                    {"op": "+", "args": [1.0, "Kn"]}
                                                ]
                                            },
                                            "α"
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                }
            },
            "equations": [],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "default_conditions",
                    "description": "Default parameters: Kn=1.0, α=1.0 (transition regime, perfect accommodation). f_D = (1+1)/(1+2×1×2/1) = 2/5 = 0.4 exactly. This is the canonical transition-regime reference point where gas-phase flux is reduced to 40% of the continuum value.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "f_D", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.4, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-15}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "continuum_limit",
                    "description": "Near-continuum regime: Kn=0.001, α=1.0. f_D = 1.001/1.002002 ≈ 0.99900. As Kn → 0, f_D → 1: the correction is negligible and J → J_c. At Kn=0.001 the deviation from unity is only 0.1%, confirming the continuum limit behavior.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"Kn": 0.001},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "f_D", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.9990000019960038, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "low_accommodation",
                    "description": "Reduced accommodation coefficient: Kn=1.0, α=0.1 (10% sticking probability). f_D = 2/(1+2×2/0.1) = 2/41 ≈ 0.04878. Lowering α from 1 to 0.1 reduces f_D from 0.4 to ≈0.04878 — a 8× reduction — because the 2Kn(1+Kn)/α term grows tenfold. Exercises the α wiring in the denominator.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"α": 0.1},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "f_D", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.04878048780487805, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "high_kn_transition",
                    "description": "Deep transition regime: Kn=10.0, α=1.0. f_D = 11/(1+220) = 11/221 ≈ 0.04977. At Kn=10 the flux is reduced to about 5% of the continuum value. Confirms the monotone decrease of f_D with increasing Kn.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"Kn": 10.0},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "f_D", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.049773755656108594, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "free_molecular_asymptote",
                    "description": "Near free-molecular limit: Kn=1000.0, α=1.0. f_D = 1001/2002001 ≈ 5.00×10⁻⁴. The asymptotic prediction α/(2Kn) = 1/2000 = 5×10⁻⁴ differs by only 0.005%, confirming that for Kn ≫ 1 the Dahneke correction scales as α/(2Kn). Flux is reduced to ~0.05% of the continuum value.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"Kn": 1000.0},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "f_D", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.000499999750249875, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-9}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "near_transition_perfect_acc",
                    "description": "Moderate Kn=0.1, α=1.0: beginning of the transition regime. f_D = 1.1/(1+2×0.1×1.1) = 1.1/1.22 ≈ 0.90164. At Kn=0.1 the flux is reduced to about 90% of the continuum value — a small but non-negligible correction. Exercises the Kn wiring in both numerator and denominator.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"Kn": 0.1},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "f_D", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.9016393442622952, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                }
            ],
            "examples": [
                {
                    "id": "fD_vs_knudsen_number",
                    "description": "Sweep Knudsen number Kn from 0.001 to 1000 log-spaced at perfect accommodation α=1. f_D decreases monotonically from ≈1 in the continuum limit to ≈α/(2Kn) in the free-molecular limit. The transition region around Kn ≈ 1 shows the characteristic rollover from the near-unity plateau to the power-law decay.",
                    "initial_state": {"type": "per_variable", "values": {}},
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "Kn",
                                "range": {"start": 0.001, "stop": 1000.0, "count": 61, "scale": "log"}
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "fD_vs_Kn",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Dahneke correction factor f_D as a function of Knudsen number Kn at α=1. Approaches 1 in the continuum regime (Kn ≪ 1) and decays as α/(2Kn) in the free-molecular regime (Kn ≫ 1).",
                            "x": {"variable": "Kn",  "label": "Knudsen number Kn"},
                            "y": {"variable": "f_D", "label": "Correction factor f_D (dimensionless)"}
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "fD_vs_accommodation",
                    "description": "Sweep accommodation coefficient α from 0.01 to 1.0 log-spaced at Kn=1.0 (transition regime). At α=1, f_D=0.4; as α decreases the denominator 1+2Kn(1+Kn)/α grows and f_D → 0. Illustrates that poor accommodation strongly suppresses the effective flux even at moderate Kn.",
                    "initial_state": {"type": "per_variable", "values": {}},
                    "parameters": {"Kn": 1.0},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "α",
                                "range": {"start": 0.01, "stop": 1.0, "count": 51, "scale": "log"}
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "fD_vs_alpha",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Dahneke correction factor f_D vs. accommodation coefficient α at Kn=1. f_D drops toward zero as α → 0 (the 2Kn(1+Kn)/α term diverges) and reaches 0.4 at α=1 (perfect accommodation). Shows the strong sensitivity to α in the transition regime.",
                            "x": {"variable": "α",   "label": "Accommodation coefficient α"},
                            "y": {"variable": "f_D", "label": "Correction factor f_D (dimensionless)"}
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}
